(494, 'England Rugby\'s Courtney Lawes Gives You His 6-Move Workout', 'At 6’7”, 109kg, Lawes is well suited to his role as England’s enforcer. Tackle his workout today', '<p><em>Standing in his shadow, it&rsquo;s immediately apparent that Courtney Lawes&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https://www.menshealth.com/uk/workouts/a759746/these-rugby-workouts-will-build-strength-speed-and-mental-resilience/\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">has won the genetic lottery &ndash;</a>&nbsp;a winning ticket England will be looking to cash in. Having got into the sport comparatively late &ndash; he picked up his first rugby ball at 15 &ndash; Lawes was awarded his first England cap just five years later by legendary lock forward Martin Johnson.</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>Since then he has been spearheading a route to the top of his sport, earning the nickname &#39;Black Javelin&#39; from his England teammates as he goes. And for good reason. His whiplash and wince-inducing tackle on France&rsquo;s Jules Plisson during 2015&#39;s Six Nations now has more than&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S3QDOWk1qIo\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">one million hits on YouTube</a>&nbsp;&ndash; by comparison Jonny Wilkinson&rsquo;s World Cup-winning drop goal has fewer than 250,000.</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>A gentle giant off the field, Lawes is keen to play down his role as one-man wrecking ball. &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t go out looking for big hits, I just want to play the game and perform for my team and my country,&rdquo; he says. But while he doesn&rsquo;t care for clickbait, the potential impact his plays have on the fans should not be undersold. When going to war in search of a Grand Slam, Lawes&rsquo; ability to turn the crowd into an extra man could prove invaluable.</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>Sure, second rows are meant to hit rucks, make tackles and set mauls rumbling &ndash; Lawes does that too &ndash; but in this championship year he&rsquo;s also looking to expand his arsenal: &ldquo;I want to get my hands on the ball, I want to carry more and make a difference going forward,&rdquo; he says, this time with a more menacing glint in his eye. This&rsquo;ll come as unwelcome news to the teams standing between England and victory, which now have nowhere to hide in either attack or defence.</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>At 6&rsquo;7&rdquo;, 109kg and covered in tribal tattoos, Lawes is well suited to his role as England&rsquo;s enforcer. However, it&rsquo;s not his huge frame that sets him apart. International rugby is a sport played by mountain men, but size, skill and speed are a package that&rsquo;s hard to come by. Too often on TV you see big men fumble forward or run at full speed, only to realise they&rsquo;re going nowhere fast. Which is where his, and England&rsquo;s, specially designed power workout comes in.</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>&ldquo;Whether it&rsquo;s&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https://www.menshealth.com/uk/building-muscle/a25905969/power-clean-complete-guide/\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">plyometrics or power cleaning</a>, the aim is to see how quickly you can shift heavy weight,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s the best way to develop fast-twitch muscles.&rdquo; The same fast-twitch fibres that get him from breakdown to half-back in breakneck speed.</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>But while Lawes&rsquo; pre-tournament preparation is nearly over (medical teams are also preparing to come forth and carry home his victims) your journey to becoming a weekend warrior with Lawes-like impact is only just beginning. Between now and the first whistle, you now have the opportunity to follow in his oversized footsteps and build a cup-winning physique &ndash; whether you&rsquo;ve cashed in a genetic lottery ticket, or not.</em></p>\\r\\n', 19, 83, 'True', '2019-02-02', '2029-12-31', './images/newsCms/Data/awes-1549018852.jpg', './images/newsCms/Data/thumb/918449_resized896858.jpg', 0, 'True'),
(495, 'Rich Froning\'s CrossFit Workout That You Can Do At Home', 'Push your fitness to the extreme with this heart-pumping workout designed by Rich Froning', '<p>You&rsquo;ll never see a&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https://www.menshealth.com/uk/fitness/lukas-hoegberg-crossfit-veteran-gives-mh-his-ultimate-training-tips\\\">stodgy pro CrossFitter&nbsp;</a>&ndash; these guys come in one size and&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https://www.menshealth.com/uk/healthy/symptoms-treatment/4-ways-to-get-lean\\\">that&rsquo;s lean.</a></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>But don&rsquo;t expect to catch&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rich_Froning_Jr.\\\">Rich Froning</a>&nbsp;&ndash; the CrossFit Games Champion for four consecutive years &ndash; on a long run: his high-octane circuits use the&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https://www.menshealth.com/uk/fitness/cardio-exercise/ultimate-Tabata-workout\\\">Tabata format&nbsp;</a>to&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https://www.menshealth.com/uk/building-muscle/melt-fat-with-the-crossfit-bodyweight-workout\\\">scorch fat and reveal the muscle beneath.</a>&nbsp;And luckily for you, or not (whatever way you want to look at it), we have one of his workouts for you to try. What&#39;s more, it can be done in the comfort of your own home. Just make sure to open a windor or two, because this is going to be tough. But did you really expect anyting else?</p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Do 8 rounds of each exercise before progressing. Rest 60sec between each move, but stay strict with your timings &ndash; max effort and low rest will seriously spike your metabolism</p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\\r\\n', 19, 83, 'True', '2019-02-02', '2029-12-31', './images/newsCms/Data/froning.jpg', './images/newsCms/Data/thumb/768329_resized109116.jpg', 0, 'True'),
(496, '4 Guys Who Went Bald Before 30 Tell You Why It Doesn’t Matter', 'Is hair loss freaking you out? Here\'s why it shouldn\'t', '<p><em><img alt=\\\"image\\\" src=\\\"https://hips.hearstapps.com/ame-prod-menshealth-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/main/thumbs/36874/willis.jpg?crop=1xw:0.6680851063829787xh;center,top&amp;resize=480:*\\\" /></em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em><a href=\\\"https://www.menshealth.com/uk/style/how-to-slow-down-hair-loss\\\">Hair loss happens</a>. It happens a lot.</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>The American Hair Loss Association estimates that two out of every three men will start to lose at least some of their hair by the time they&rsquo;re 35. When they&rsquo;re 50, around 85% will have significant thinning.</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>And when the hair starts to go, well, there aren&rsquo;t many guys who go, &ldquo;Oh cool, just what I was hoping would happen.&rdquo; In 2013, researchers in Berlin conducted a major study of the psychosomatic effects of hair loss, and concluded that even minor balding could lead to &ldquo;an enormous emotional burden with low self-confidence, impaired quality of life, and even psychological disorders.&rdquo;</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>And consider this distressing statistic, from a 2009 survey conducted by the International Society of Hair Restoration Surgery. Almost 60% of guys would rather have a full head of hair than money or friends. That&rsquo;s right, living alone on the street without a friend in the world would be fine, as long as you&rsquo;re not bald.</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>What in the actual hell, guys?</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em><img alt=\\\"image\\\" src=\\\"https://hips.hearstapps.com/ame-prod-menshealth-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/main/assets/Statham_hair.jpg?resize=480:*\\\" /></em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em><strong><a href=\\\"https://www.menshealth.com/uk/style/how-to-slow-down-thinning-hair\\\">(Related: How to prevent your hair from thinning)</a></strong></em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>It&rsquo;s amazing how far people will go to save their hair. They&rsquo;ll spend thousands of dollars on supposed cures, or submit to hair restoration surgery &ndash; we&rsquo;re looking at you, Donald Trump and whatever that is on your head &ndash; or try drugs that might be doing more harm than good. In place of all those extreme measures, there&rsquo;s a better way to treat baldness, a way that will save you money and time and endless stress.</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>Are you ready for it?</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>Just let it happen.</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>Go bald. And don&rsquo;t give a shit. Don&rsquo;t believe that&rsquo;s possible? We talked to four accomplished, well-traveled men with one thing in common: They&rsquo;re all bald&mdash;in fact, they all started losing their hair before the age of 30&mdash;and they all don&rsquo;t care.</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>How&rsquo;d they reach that magical place of acceptance? Let&rsquo;s find out.</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>He didn&rsquo;t have time to worry about his hair, he says. &ldquo;I went on to serve in the Scots Guards. I traveled the world. I was a bodyguard for some of the biggest names in rock n&rsquo; roll. I&rsquo;m a five handicap.&rdquo; Once you&rsquo;re busy living, Portis says, &ldquo;You don&rsquo;t worry about the top of your head.&rdquo;</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2><em>Find a Bald Role Model</em></h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>For all the worrying men do about losing their hair, you&rsquo;d think more of them would remember that some very badass and successful men are and were comfortably bald.</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>Like who? Like Tyrese Gibson, Vin Diesel, Billy Zane, Taye Diggs, Stanley Tucci, Pitbull, Mark Strong, Matt Lauer, Isaac Hayes, Mark Messier, Andre Agassi, Albert Pujols, Stone Cold Stone Austin, Marvelous Marvin Hagler, Lex Luthor, Brian Urlacher, Bruce Willis, Jason Statham, Evander Holyfield, and Michael Jordan.</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>Can&rsquo;t a man find some peace in that company?</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>Peter Woodke is a veteran attorney in the Boise, Idaho area. He saw his hair going early, but he found some role models out in the world to erase any trauma.</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>&ldquo;As my hair was thinning further, I realised I knew guys through work who are bald and are highly motivated individuals,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;I figure they haven&rsquo;t it let it affect them, so why should it with me?&rdquo;</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2><em>Take Care of the Rest of You</em></h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>Losing hair is often beyond control. It just happens for a myriad of natural biological reasons. But there are countless other factors in how a man presents himself that are entirely his responsibility.</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>Paul Moynan is a rock of a man. After serving multiple tours in Middle East combat with the Royal Marines, he keeps himself in top shape. As he flies back in forth from London to Dubai to New York to North Africa for the maritime firm he leads, he&rsquo;s always dressed to the nines. The women who run into him on a daily basis are not worried that he went bald years ago.</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>&ldquo;If you&rsquo;re looking healthy, if you&rsquo;re well dressed and you present yourself professionally, there isn&rsquo;t a woman alive who&rsquo;s going to look past you because of your hair,&rdquo; he says.</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>Forget the surgeries and drugs. Save that money for a life adventure. Something that matters. Don&rsquo;t bother covering it up with hats, and please, for the love of all that&rsquo;s holy, don&rsquo;t attempt a combover. Moynan and every other bald and proud man we interviewed for this story agreed on one thing: Women will always choose the smoothly bald man over the insecure weed who&rsquo;s desperately hiding his head from the world.</em></p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>It&rsquo;s just not what a man does.</em></p>\\r\\n', 19, 0, 'True', '2019-02-02', '2029-12-31', './images/newsCms/Data/baldies.jpg', './images/newsCms/Data/thumb/330326_resized868051.jpg', 0, 'True'),
