(63, 'Asmaa Al Zohairy', 'TDAthletics Trainer and Coach', '', '', '', '', 'https://www.instagram.com/azee.zohairy/', '<p>Egyptian Indoor Rowing Champion&nbsp;<br />\r\nEgypt&#39;s Nike Ambassador&nbsp;<br />\r\nTDAthletics Trainer and Coach Aspiring Rowing Athlete</p>\r\n', '422341_resized212893.jpg', '860808_resized416254.jpg', 'male', '2018-09-26 04:10:48', '2018-09-26 04:16:11', 'Show', NULL, 'Athlete'),
(64, 'Ramy Ashour', '', '1987 - Sep - 30', '', '', 'https://www.facebook.com/TeamRamyAshour/', 'https://www.instagram.com/ramyashourr/', '<p>Ramy is one of the PSA World Tour&rsquo;s biggest contenders. From a very young age, Ramy secured many championship titles, made his mark in the world of squash and continues to show he means business on the court wherever he plays...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ramy is a two times World juniors champion, a two times World seniors (mens) Champion and holds the World Number One spot on the PSA world rankings. Today at the prime of his game, 25 year old Ramy boasts multiple exemplary titles including being the first player ever to take home the World Junior trophy twice, and the World Men&#39;s championship twice. He was also awarded PSA player of the year three times along with many other international titles to his name<br />\r\nRamy&#39;s official Website&nbsp;http://www.ramyashouracademy.com/</p>\r\n', '533216_resized791556.jpg', '746336_resized780648.jpg', 'male', '2018-09-26 04:21:30', NULL, 'Show', NULL, 'Athlete'),
(65, 'Nour el Sherbini', '', '1995 - Nov - 1', '', '', 'https://www.facebook.com/nourelsherbini/', 'https://www.instagram.com/noursherbini/', '<p>Nour was born and raised in the Egyptian city of Alexandria. She started playing Squash at age six, and was already participating in tournaments before she was eight!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Her brother Omar el Sherbini played an important role to keep her interested in Squash as she would spend time watching him and learning from his sessions. But she confirms that sport runs all through her family. &quot;My father used to be a football player and a good swimmer. Also my mum was a good athlete&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Interestingly, there was never a competing sport for her time. It was squash aged six and nothing else has been added.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As she explains: &quot;By the time I gained more confidence and became more steady that made me able to win most of the titles of the local tournaments in Egypt, till reaching the British open and my first international tittles. My first bjo title [British Junior Open] was such a push for more titles starting from under 13 years old till under 15, titles in a row.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Only a few months after her thirteenth birthday, Nour joined WISPA in early 2009, and in April, she announced her arrival by only losing to world top liner Engy Kheirallah in a tight 3/1 at the Heliopolis Open. Having reached the final of the ATCO Miro event in June, also in Cairo, it was only another strong performance from Kheirallah that thwarted her bid for a first WISPA Tour title.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But then came the World Junior Individual in Chennai, India, in which she caused a sensation by becoming world under 19 champion at the age of 13.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As she explained: &quot;Reaching the most important moment of my life, I was chosen to represent Egypt in the world open junior championship taking place in Chennai, India. To win the title was a dream, but to take it and feel the taste of victory was a dream came true. Adding the World Team title made it looks extraordinary&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In just four years on the WSA World Tour, Nour El Sherbini has risen a remarkable 208 places in the women&rsquo;s rankings to occupy the world No.7 spot at the tender age of 16-years-old. Many players spend years battling through competitions but the rate at which Sherbini has progressed to a world-beating standard has without doubt thrown down the gauntlet to Nicol David for the next couple of years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Her first professional competition came in the Heliopolis Open as a qualifier, and made it through to the first round. The following January she won the British Junior Under 19&rsquo;s Open at the age of fourteen, at which point she had already broken into the world&rsquo;s top50. She returned to Heliopolis in 2010 to claim her first WSA title at the event in which she had made her debut the year before. The following year, still rapidly climbing the rankings and sitting at No36, she won the Alexandria International Open as 5th seed and finished off the year by reaching round two of the World Open as a qualifier.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So far in 2012 the signs have continued to look good for the Egyptian starlet after semi-final appearances in Tournament of Champions in New York, as well as in the KL Open in Malaysia. These results tipped Sherbini into the Top20 mix, but undeterred by the daunting prospect of facing the big names in the tour, she stunned Londoners at the O2 Arena by reaching the final of the WSA World Series Platinum Allam British Open event, only quelled by the current queen of the women&rsquo;s game Nicol David. If Sherbini&rsquo;s progression continues at this rate, it won&rsquo;t be long before David&rsquo;s No.1 spot may be put under question.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In 2012 Nour also added new highlights to her career by reaching the final of the prestigious British open in May to be the youngest ever and the first Egyptian to reach the final of this prestigious event against World no.1 Nicol David. She also created history one month after when her ranking raised to world number 7 to be the youngest ever to get in the top 10 on the world at only age of 16.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Making it extraordinary Nour won the World Junior title in July 2012 to add 2 world titles to her record.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As she says &ldquo; Reaching world number 7 and adding another world junior title only adds on me extra work and responsibility to be consistent and able to compete at this level keeping my ranking high and achieving my dream&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nour aims now to keep her ranking and also to achieve a new record which is the youngest and the first Egyptian to win the world Open title.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It may be stating the obvious, but this delightful girl with a prodigious talent and a maturity of play beyond her years is likely to build from these early successes and become another enduring WISPA junior and senior star.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nour&#39;s Official Website&nbsp;http://www.nourelsherbini.com</p>\r\n', '913070_resized9748.jpg', '489329_resized576250.jpg', 'male', '2018-09-26 04:24:39', NULL, 'Show', NULL, 'Athlete');
